   <titles>
      <title>Distance of a Point from a Hyperplane – Illustration</title>
   </titles>
   <body>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>In <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                  </math> and in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                  </math> we illustrate what we mean by ‘distance of a point from a hyperplalne’.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>In <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                  </math> a hyperplane is a line. So we will develop a formula which computes the distance of a point <math>
                     <latex>Q</latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                  </math> from a line <math>
                     <latex>L</latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
            <para align="center">
               <para.body>
                  <media xmlns="" type="image" active="1" inline="0">
                     <img src="ims/DistancePointHyperplane_2D.gif" height="225" width="434"/>
                  </media>
                  <info>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>Connections from <math>
                              <latex>Q</latex>
                           </math> to points on <math>
                              <latex>L</latex>
                           </math> have varying lengths. So what shall we mean by ‘distance of <math>
                              <latex>Q</latex>
                           </math> from <math>
                              <latex>L</latex>
                           </math>?</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </info>
               </para.body>
            </para>
            <para>
               <para.body>Given a line <math>
                     <latex>L</latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                  </math> and a point <math>
                     <latex>Q</latex>
                  </math>, there is always exactly one point <math>
                     <latex>R</latex>
                  </math> on <math>
                     <latex>L</latex>
                  </math> which is closest to <math>
                     <latex>Q</latex>
                  </math>. So we define the distance from <math>
                     <latex>Q</latex>
                  </math> to <math>
                     <latex>L</latex>
                  </math> to be the distance from <math>
                     <latex>Q</latex>
                  </math> to <math>
                     <latex>R</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>In <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                  </math> a hyperplane is a plane in the conversational sense. So we will develop a formula which computes the distance of a point <math>
                     <latex>Q</latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                  </math> from a plane <math>
                     <latex>L</latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
            <para align="center">
               <para.body/>
            </para>
            <para>
               <para.body>Given a plane <math>
                     <latex>\Pi</latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                  </math> and a point <math>
                     <latex>Q</latex>
                  </math>, there is always exactly one point <math>
                     <latex>R</latex>
                  </math> on <math>
                     <latex>\Pi</latex>
                  </math> whose distance from <math>
                     <latex>R</latex>
                  </math> is less than the distance of any other point on <math>
                     <latex>\Pi</latex>
                  </math> from <math>
                     <latex>Q</latex>
                  </math>. Thus we define the distance from <math>
                     <latex>Q</latex>
                  </math> to <math>
                     <latex>\Pi</latex>
                  </math> to be the distance from <math>
                     <latex>Q</latex>
                  </math> to the point on <math>
                     <latex>\Pi</latex>
                  </math> closest to <math>
                     <latex>Q</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
   </body>
